'''Haustafel''' (German meaning literally "house-table") is a generally used as a theological term for proper domestic or household order in the Christian home. This term was first used in Martin Luther's commentary on family member duties as prescribed in scriptural passages such as Ephesians chapters 5 and 6. It is intended to immediately imply the highly practical nature of the instructions: an individual's "haustefel duties" are not related to abstract beliefs they are expected to hold to, but rather to specific actions they are expected to perform.